article.headline: Detroit slump reaches eight of last 11
article.story:
INDIANAPOLIS (AP) -- Detroit Shock coach Bill Laimbeer tried to
choose his words carefully after his team's latest loss.

"The double standard continues in refereeing the game," he
said after his team was outscored 24-9 from the free throw line
Friday night in a 62-57 loss to the Indiana Fever.

Tamika Catchings had 20 points, 14 rebounds and five assists to
lead the Fever, who got into the bonus with 11:42 to play.

"She has good instincts to go get the ball," Indiana coach
Brian Winters said of the 6-foot-1 forward. "No matter what size a
player is, with good instincts she can get the ball."

Detroit was held below 60 points for the second time this
season, shooting 42 percent from the field.

"By getting into the bonus early early, we were able to hit
free throws and that helped us down the stretch," Catchings said.
"We played good team defense. That helped us because our outside
shooting was off."

Indiana had only one field goal in the final three minutes,
scoring eight of its final 10 points on free throws.

The Fever (10-6) were helped by a season-high 13 points from
Jurgita Streimikyte, making her second start of the season. It
marked the fewest games Indiana needed to reach 10 victories. The
Fever got their 10th win in their 17th game in 2003.

Detroit (7-9), led by Deanna Nolan with 19 points and Sheila
Lambert with 13, suffered its eighth loss in 11 games.

The Fever missed all of their 15 shots from 3-point range,
failing to score from behind the arc for the first time in their
six-year history -- a span of 179 games.

Indiana also helped itself by recording a 24-13 advantage in
turnovers. However, Indiana only scored 16 points following Detroit
turnovers and Detroit scored 14 following Indiana's miscues. The 24
turnovers by the Shock were their season-high.

Indiana led 58-57 when Deanna Jackson and Catchings each hit one
of two free throws with less than 30 seconds to go, and the Shock
were forced to foul to gain possession. The Fever missed two free
throws with 14.2 seconds to go, but Catchings snared an offensive
rebound.

Nolan's wild 3-point attempt was off target and Catchings hit
two free throws to clinch the victory.

The victory was the fifth straight for Indiana over Detroit,
including two this season. Indiana has won seven of its last nine
home games against the Shock, including two this year which gave
the Fever a 10-9 advantage in the all-time series.

The teams will meet again Sunday in Detroit.

"If we just cut down on our turnovers, we'll have a better
opportunity to win," Nolan said. "If we play with intensity,
we'll get the win."

Indiana opened a 12-3 lead in the game's first seven minutes as
Detroit hit only one of its first 10 shots from the field and had
five quick turnovers.

The Shock tied the game at 16 and the score was tied three more
times before halftime. Indiana led 28-26 at the break on a shot at
the buzzer, but officials reversed the call after reviewing it on
videotape.
